original_text: I give this production two stars for a valiant effort at Victorian atmosphere in terms of sets and costumes, especially with such a tiny budget. However, too many producer/directors overextend themselves by attempting to act in their own films, now matter how large or small the production. Anthony D.P. Mann commits the cardinal sin of playing the title role, even though he in no way resembles the character. Sadly, he is no Orson Welles. He should have spent more time teaching his amateur supporting cast how to properly project their characters to the camera.

original_text:
The story the movie attempts to portray is your average Greek myth. In this case it's a modified Defeat of the Minotaur myth, but to be honest I couldn't get through the whole movie, just the first half. There were to many moments that lead me to lose interest in the movie.

The art is also very disconcerting in the regards to how the characters mouths seen to never synch up to the sound. I am a fan of animated movies but this seems more like a fan fiction version than an actual movie.

I am unsure why this most humanistic and compelling film has been generally rated so poorly; this fact is something I find almost disconcerting. original_text: Todd Solondz's approach to dark humor is that in order to get to the supposed humor you must travel through the dark forest that is the American Psyche. And once you've arrived, you may not even feel like laughing. It may be more of a very faint chuckle and the words "Oh my God" as you realize you've met these people before. They're the estranged Aunts and Cousins, those exes you really wish you wouldn't have dated, your own Mother. But this is Solondz's speciality: taking us on a detailed tour of the underbelly of the American Experience.

original_text:
This was certainly a family friendly film that gave the audience some "basic" understanding around Norse Mythology. In some ways it reminded my of Jurassic park. The violence in the movie is "mild" which is not surprising given it's PG-13 rating. Personally I would have preferred something much more Viking or Norse-esque.

The story line was fun and for anyone with children who like a little adventure this is a great one to share.

David Roach, Independent Author of the "Marauder Series"
Web Page - http://marauderseries.blogspot.com/
The Books - http://www.amazon.com/gp/bookseries/B019SCYN26

original_text: I was so disappointed in this movie. I'd watched the trailer and from what I saw, thought it's be a great movie...It could have been so much more. The little dab of romance you're led to believe will develop fizzles out. Worst of all, no one speaks English, so you're reading the lines all the way through the movie, which is something I hate doing. (My personal pet peeve). What little back story that's told is also a bit of a disappointment.

original_text: One won't find anything more in this Norwegian film than one would normally expect to find in a SyFy channel "made-for-cable" production except perhaps the "subtitles." One gets the sense that this is the updated, CGI Norwegian version of the old, hokey Danish flick, "Reptilicus." The only consolation is that at least, even with mediocre CGI effects, Ragnarok-Reptilicus doesn't look like a puppet with "strings."

original_text:
Having read a few works on the life of Marie Curie, I am not certain why the director chose to portray her as such a narcissistic and selfish individual. The characters standoffish attitude detracts from the meaningful works that the real life individual accomplished.
Pacing of the film was weird. The film spent an exorbitant amount of time on future nuclear disasters and atomic weapons. A LOT of time.
Over all I cannot say that I enjoyed the film and would not recommend it to others.

original_text:
AMAZON PRIME VIDEO

I'm not sure of the accuracy of the details portrayed here, but this production appears to make an interesting telling of the majority of the life of Madame Curie.

The acting is quite believable, and the sets are excellent. I liked how they skipped forward in time to depict both highly positive and highly negative results of the discovery of radioactivity.

The movie is paced rather slowly, and at times bends towards being a soap opera. It does a nice job of blending science and the human element.

3.5 STARS

I did NOT like Jeremy Scott. I thought his temper tantrum reminded me the "terrible" two's with little children. All the contestants work hard and deserve to be treated with respect.
Love Heidi and Tim Gunn and I wish Tim was a judge with a "floating" judge weekly.
I saw the last episode and was aghast at the winner, nothing wearable at all but the runner up has a mentorship with Amazon and yes he had wearable clothing. Alas those who made beautifully draped and cut clothing got sent home fast. I find this disappointing.

This movie starts off with an interesting premise, moves quickly to reanimating a human, and then implodes under the weight of confusing plot and backstory.

Theres just too much going on here that stretches credulity- even in a movie about bringing the dead to life.

A simpler, cleaner plot with ramifications taking place outside the sole sole setting (A dark laboratory) would have been better.

Its a shame. Sometimes less is more.

original_text: The best shark-hunting-humans film I've seen. Simple and believable set-up and excellent unspooling of the terror as we become invested in the characters. The shark doesn't become some sort of over-the-top monster, just remains a predator.  The intercuts of the shark and the swimmers is a slow-build with realistic shocks, and I didn't for a moment get a feeling of some kind of special-effects at work. Very well done.

original_text:
So many films have tried to reach the level of thrill and authenticity that Spielberg captured with JAWS. So many have failed - Deep Blue Sea, the Shallows, Open Water, Shark Night 3D.... the list goes on and on.

The Reef is the closest any shark film has come - maybe because it drew from actual events, or maybe because the director is an Aussie star with several great creature-features to his name (you should see Black Water if you like crocodile movies). Either way, it works.

original_text: I like the series but it walks a very fine line with the approach and perspective on violence. In the bonus material the lead character is described has having a good moral center. Seriously? This is someone who commits violence and murder for a living, and in one case of mistaken identity where he murders the wrong person, he attempts to make amends to the family with money but otherwise seems unshaken and unremorseful. Maybe if there are more seasons this will be addressed and resolved as part of the lead character's story arc.
